Inclusiveness

Target IP: 192.168.170.14

Scanning



There are three TCP ports open on the host machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP. FTP looks interesting as it allows anonymous login with writeable permission! I will start my enumeration with FTP first.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

There are no files for us to download. However, we have write permissions meaning we can upload files to the directory.

Port 80: HTTP

Doing a simple directory search gives us plenty of information.



It mentions robots.txt is not readable. However, using the command sudo curl -s --user-agent Googlebot http://192.168.170.14/robots.txt -v I was able to. There is a disallowed entry called /secret_information/.


Browsing to /secret_information/ leads us to the page above about DNS Zone Transfer Attack. There are two buttons (english and spanish) which can be used to change the text of the page. It looks like the application includes the page depending on which button the user presses.


For example, pressing the english button shows us the parameter called lang. Maybe we can use directory traversal or LFI attacks?


And bingo! The host is vulnerable to LFI attacks. I was able to include the /etc/passwd file from the host's system.


I am also able to access the test.txt file I uploaded through FTP using this attack. I browsed to http://192.168.170.14/secret_information/?lang=../../../../../../../var/ftp/pub/test.txt. So we should be able to include our reverse shell script and access it by HTTP to gain a connection back.

Exploitation


I used PHP PentestMonkey script for the reverse shell. The parameters ip and port were changed to point to my local machine. Then I put this script inside shell.php.


I uploaded the shell.php using FTP inside the pub directory.



Then I started a listener on port 8443, visited http://192.168.170.14/secret_information/?lang=../../../../../../../var/ftp/pub/shell.php from my browser, and got a reverse shell connection back from the target machine. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting binary called rootshell which is located inside /home/tom.


Hmmm... this script checks if the current user is tom. If it is then a root shell is spawned, otherwise it will not work. We should be able to bypass this.



By using PATH variable manipulation, we are tom with root privileges.
